      <h1>Portland!</h1>
        <h2>Portland is green AF, so go outside and explore:</h2>
        <p><u>Forest Park</u> - The countries largest city park is only ½ mile from our doorstep! With over 80 miles of trails this is a great place to go for a walk without driving. Whether you have an hour or all day, there are routes and options for all. </p>
        <a href="https://www.pdxmonthly.com/articles/2017/5/15/eight-essential-forest-park-hikes" title="hikes" target="_blank">Click here to see top hikes to do while visiting</a><br><br>
        <img src="https://i.pinimg.com/originals/df/b1/42/dfb142bd6e2343a2358437c90a65dbd0.gif" alt="Hikes Map"><br>
        <p><u>St. Johns/Peninsula Park</u> - St. Johns is the closest neighborhood in Portland to us. And it’s a cute super cute one. A small movie theater, bars, great restaurants and amazing parks make it a must on any visit to Portland. Cathedral Park under the St Johns Bridge is a great place to take a stroll before dinner or to have a picnic.
          The bigger park in the neighborhood is Peninsula Park and there you will find the closest disc golf course to us.
          Ask Sid to borrow some discs! But don’t invite him if you decide to go two or three days before the wedding. He’s got waayyy too many things to do at that time.</p><h4>add nail emoji</h4><br>
        <p><u>Skyline Tavern</u> - The one and only bar near us, just 2 miles from the house. And would you look at that! They are a non-profit bar (betcha didn’t know those existed, right? Well, welcome to Portland)! All proceeds go to scholarships for film school students.
          With great music 6 nights a week, a variety of local beer/cider options, yummy food, amazing outdoor seating, a ping pong table and BYO-BBQ, Skyline Tavern is a little taste of how awesome Portland can be.
          And it’s just around the corner from us. <a href="https://skytav.com" title="Pre-party" target="_blank">This is where we'll pre-party on Friday evening!</a>
        </p>
        <p>
          <u>Sauvies Island</u> - What was once an island full of Wapato and mud is now a thriving agricultural community within the city limits.
          Not only are there great farm stands to check out (Kruger’s Farm) but Portland’s own river beach on the east side of the island along the mighty Columbia River.
          A great place to visit so you can say you’ve been both in WA and OR (the river separates both states) and you get the chance to maybe see some naked people in the nude section lololol because, why not?
        </p><br>
        <h1>To escape the heat, check out these places:</h1>
        <p>
